@node "dRE!WhO" "dRE!WhO"
 
 @{b}How to use the door...@{ub}
 
 It`s very simple to use dre!who, just enter @{b}WHO ?@{ub} at the mainline to see the
 command template.
 
 @{u}Some examples:@{uu} 
 
 @{b}WHO 3@{ub}       - dre!who looks now in it`s homedir/configs for a file called
               who.3 parses the % sequences and displays the
               whostyle.
 
 @{b}WHO U@{ub}       - will monitor all available nodes
               (@{b}@{u}NOTE:@{ub}@{uu} At this time dre!who hasn`t a own monitor mode, i use
                      instead the original from fame, in later version it
                      will support the spymode with it`s own styles)
 
 @{b}WHO FORCE@{ub}   - will try to open who.data which will be created by the
               dRE!WhO-CfG door to get the choosen default styles and try`s
               override the hiddenflag, if you have access to it you are now
               able to spy hidden nodes, otherwise you`ll see nothing :)

 @{b}WHO 2 FORCE@{ub} - The same as above but it try`s to access the who.2
               config-file for the display.
 
 See @{"the configfiles" link "Config-files" 0} and @{"dre!who-Config" link "dRE!WhO-Config" 0} for more infos
@endnode

@node "dRE!WhO-Config" "dRE!WhO-Config"
 
 @{b}Who to use the config-editor...?@{ub}
 
 The dRE!WhO-CfG is written to be used from the DOOR config commands.
 The installer-script will built in the command correctly (I hope :))
 
 Just call the `@{b}W@{ub}` command a chhose the option `@{b}[14] DOOR CONFIG@{ub}`, here
 you`ll see a command called `@{b}dRE!WhO-Config@{ub}` select it and you`ll see
 a list of all found styles in the homedir/configs of dre!who. 
 
 Now you can select the different styles by pressing the correct number
 of it, the the confog door will display you the who-style as example
 and if you have found your preferred style press `S` at the command
 line to save you personal prefs. Now dre!who always looks for an entry
 of your account and display`s you the saved style.

 Also you can switch on the Monitor mode, then the who door will monitor
 always the node. 

 @{b}Just configure your favorite style out.@{ub}
 
 Of coz you can always use the WHO commandline template to show other
 styles or options.
@endnode

@node "Config-files" "The Config-files"
 
 @{b}How to create own output-styles...?@{ub}
 
 Create in the homedir/configs of dre!who (doors:dre!who) a file called who.<#>
 for example if you have already the 8 supllied styles in your dir then the
 the file must be named: who.5, if not the styles are starting with the
 file: who.0 then the next must be who.1 and so on.
 
 The frontend views for a file called who.frontend in the same dro as the
 door is located. If the file can`t be accessed a error message will occure.
 
 @{b}VALID CONFIGFILE COMMANDS ARE:@{ub}
 
 OUTPUTNAME
 HEADER_START
 HEADER_END
 SEPERATOR_START
 SEPERATOR_END
 FORMAT_START
 FORMAT_END
 TAILER_START
 TAILER_END
 
 Explainment of the @{"CONFIGFILE COMMANDS" link "cfgcommands" 0}
 
 @{b}VALID COMMAND SEQUENCES ARE:@{ub}

 %D -> will be replaced by the Node number
 %B -> will be replaced by the baud/cps rate
 %N -> will be replaced by users handle
 %L -> will be replaced by users location
 %S -> will be replaced by the node action
 %C -> Will bre replaced by the Chat abillity of the node

 Here is a @{"simple configfile example" link "configexample" 0}.
@endnode

@node "cfgcommands" "CONFIGFILE COMMANDS"
 
 @{b}Description of all config-file commands@{ub}

 OUTPUTNAME      - Includes the Stylename, which is displayed in the config
                   door.
                   @{b}EXAMPLE:@{ub} OUTPUTNAME=Acid Style

 HEADER_START
 HEADER_END      - Between this to commands place you header, this is
                   displayed from the who door before any node info is shown.

 SEPERATOR_START 
 SEPERATOR_END   - Between this commands place the seperator line, this line
                   will be displyed between each node. Leave empty to display
                   no line between the nodes.
 FORMAT_START
 FORMAT_END      - Between this commands you must place the format line. This
                   line should include all infos you like to show in your who
                   output.
                   @{b}EXAMPLE:@{ub} %2D %-10.10B %-15.15N %-20.20S
                            Will display the Node, baud/cps rate, users handle
                            and the node action, with a length of the given
                            number in the % sequence.
                   See @{"Formatting codes" link "codes" 0} for more infos.
 TAILER_START
 TAILER_END      - Between this commands place your Tailer, this will be
                   displayed from the who door after all node infos are shown.
 
 View the @{"example Config" link "configexample" 0} for more infos.
@endnode

@node "configexample" "simple configfile example"
  ; Example configfile for dre!who v1.0 for FAME BBS System
 
 OUTPUTNAME=FAME Standard
 
 HEADER_START
    Node      User            Location              Status           Baud/Cps
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
 HEADER_END
 
 SEPERATOR_START
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
 SEPERATOR_END
 
 FORMAT_START
  # %2D| %-15.15N | %-15.15L | %-20.20S | %-10.10B
 FORMAT_END
 
 TAILER_START
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
 TAILER_END 
 
 ; End of config example
 
 @{b}The Format string will this display in your bbs on who:@{ub}

 #  2|     dr.dre/tRSi |  .PlAStiC.CitY. |         dRE!WhO v1.2 | 115200 bps

 See @{"Formatting codes" link "codes" 0} or the supplied example configs for more infos.
@endnode

@node "codes" "Formatting codes"
 
 @{b}How to use the formatting codes correctly...?@{ub}
 

 The config supports the standard ANSI C formatting sequences
 @{b}See the Examples below how to use the string formatting@{ub}
 
 %-22.22N -> [dr.dre/trsi           ]   %-22-22N -> [dr.dre/trsi           ]
 %.22-22N -> [dr.dre/trsi]              %.22.22N -> [dr.dre/trsi]    
 %22.22N  -> [           dr.dre/trsi]   %22-22N  -> [dr.dre/trsi           ]
 %-22N    -> [dr.dre/trsi           ]   %.22N    -> [dr.dre/trsi]       
 %22N     -> [           dr.dre/trsi]
 
 @{b}This is a small example who to set the % sequences correctly, each sequence
 will display an 18 char string formatted to display 22 chars, without the
 braces of coz.@{ub}
@endnode

